SIMPLE: estate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Estate
<hw>Es*tate"</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧s*t⟦amac⟧t")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estat</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tat</ets>, L. <ets>status</ets>, fr.
<ets>stare</ets> to stand. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf.
<er>State</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Settled condition or form of
existence; state; condition or circumstances of life or of any person;
situation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧When I came to man's <xex>estate</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mind not high things, but condescend to men of low
<qex>estate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Romans xii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Social standing or rank; quality; dignity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God hath imprinted his authority in several parts, upon several
<qex>estates</qex> of men.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person of high rank.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She's a duchess, a great <qex>estate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Herod on his birthday made a supper to his lords, high captains,
and chief <qex>estates</qex> of Galilee.</q> <rj><qau>Mark vi.
21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A property which a person possesses; a fortune;
possessions, esp. property in land; also, property of all kinds which a
person leaves to be divided at his death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See what a vast <qex>estate</qex> he left his son.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The state; the general body politic; the
common-wealth; the general interest; state affairs.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I call matters of <qex>estate</qex> not only the parts of
sovereignty, but whatsoever . . . concerneth manifestly any great
portion of people.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The great classes or orders of a
community or state (as the clergy, the nobility, and the commonalty of
England) or their representatives who administer the government; <as>as,
the <ex>estates</ex> of the realm (England), which are (1) the lords
spiritual, (2) the lords temporal, (3) the commons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The degree, quality, nature, and
extent of one's interest in, or ownership of, lands, tenements, etc.;
<as>as, an <ex>estate</ex> for life, for years, at will, etc.</as></def>
<rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The fourth estate</b></col>, <cd>a name often given to
the public press.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Estate
<hw>Es*tate"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To establish.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tom settle as a fortune.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To endow with an estate.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then would I . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Estate</qex> them with large land and territory.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>Estatly</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Estatlich</ent>⟦br⟧
